{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-b4d661826fe7e91f","type":"tool_result","content":"ENVIRONMENTAL DUE DILIGENCE ISSUES MEMORANDUM\nPRIVILEGED & CONFIDENTIAL — ATTORNEY WORK PRODUCT / PREPARED IN ANTICIPATION OF TRANSACTION\nTO:\nCornerstone Industrial Partners LLC (Buyer); Whitfield & Crane LLP (Buyer’s Counsel)\nFROM:\nEnvironmental Due Diligence Review\nDATE:\nNovember 1, 2024\nRE:\nEnvironmental Issues and Severity Ratings — Proposed Acquisition of 4820 Lakeshore Industrial Drive, Toledo, Lucas County, Ohio 43611 (Lucas County Parcel Nos. 18-04562-001, -002, -003) from Breckenridge Manufacturing Co.\nTRANSACTION:\nAsset Purchase Agreement dated September 1, 2024; Purchase Price $8,750,000; Lender: Great Lakes Capital Bank (Loan No. GLCB-2024-08173, $6,125,000); Closing Date: December 15, 2024\n\n1. Executive Summary\nThis memorandum summarizes the environmental issues identified during review of the Phase I Environmental Site Assessment (Phase I ESA) and supporting environmental documents for Buyer’s proposed acquisition of the approximately 14.7-acre former manufacturing/warehouse complex located at 4820 Lakeshore Industrial Drive, Toledo, Ohio (the “Property”) from Breckenridge Manufacturing Co. (“Seller”). Each issue is assigned a severity rating using the four-tier scale defined in Section 3.\nThe Greenfield Environmental Consultants Inc. Phase I ESA (dated October 25, 2024; ASTM E1527-21) identified two on-site Recognized Environmental Conditions (RECs) — (1) former trichloroethylene (TCE) vapor degreasing operations and an abandoned waste-TCE drum, and (2) former hexavalent chromium electroplating operations. The Phase I ESA also identified one Historical Recognized Environmental Condition (HREC), no Controlled Recognized Environmental Conditions (CRECs), and one de minimis condition.\nOur review identifies several matters that the Phase I ESA did not classify as RECs but that, in our judgment, warrant equivalent concern or further investigation, including: an off-site tetrachloroethylene (PCE) groundwater plume migrating toward the Property from an adjacent former dry cleaner (with the Property located within a designated Groundwater Management Zone and shallow groundwater estimated at only 8 to 15 feet below ground surface); an unregistered, unclosed 2,000-gallon waste-solvent underground storage tank (UST) of unknown status; a former outdoor drum-storage area that corresponds to the location of a documented 2003 Ohio EPA Notice of Violation; and an uncharacterized monitoring well of unknown origin near the property boundary.\nWe further identify multiple discrepancies between Seller’s representations and warranties in the Asset Purchase Agreement and the environmental record, most notably Seller’s failure to disclose the 2003 Ohio EPA Notice of Violation on Schedule 4.12(c) and the omission of two historical USTs from Schedule 4.13 (with a related potential breach of the § 4.13(b) “no UST releases/leaking” representation). These discrepancies may support a claim that the representations are breached and, potentially, that the fraud/intentional-misrepresentation exception to the indemnification cap, basket, and survival period applies.\nFinally, because the Phase I ESA identifies RECs, the Lender’s mandatory conditional requirements are triggered (Phase II ESA, Pollution Legal Liability insurance, possible remediation escrow and remediation plan, and vapor intrusion assessment), none of which have yet been satisfied. The Lender — which has placed the Property in its “Elevated Environmental Risk” category and which notes that AAI failure would expose both Borrower and the Bank to CERCLA liability — has expressly stated it will not fund the Loan based solely on a Phase I ESA that identifies RECs. The Lender also reserves the right to decline funding based on unresolved data gaps, several of which remain open.\nA total of fifty (50) distinct issues are enumerated below. A severity summary table appears in Section 12.\n\n2. Scope of Review and Documents Reviewed\n2.1 Documents Reviewed\nThe following documents were reviewed \n...LEN total chars: 58881","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b956bad2-da4b-4332-b834-7a09f6f0b7da","uuid":"7ba46fa6-3444-4072-9512-16a071188a00","timestamp":"2026-06-27T02:49:08.806Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"ENVIRONMENTAL DUE DILIGENCE ISSUES MEMORANDUM\nPRIVILEGED & CONFIDENTIAL — ATTORNEY WORK PRODUCT / PREPARED IN ANTICIPATION OF TRANSACTION\nTO:\nCornerstone Industrial Partners LLC (Buyer); Whitfield & Crane LLP (Buyer’s Counsel)\nFROM:\nEnvironmental Due Diligence Review\nDATE:\nNovember 1, 2024\nRE:\nEnvironmental Issues and Severity Ratings — Proposed Acquisition of 4820 Lakeshore Industrial Drive, Toledo, Lucas County, Ohio 43611 (Lucas County Parcel Nos. 18-04562-001, -002, -003) from Breckenridge Manufacturing Co.\nTRANSACTION:\nAsset Purchase Agreement dated September 1, 2024; Purchase Price $8,750,000; Lender: Great Lakes Capital Bank (Loan No. GLCB-2024-08173, $6,125,000); Closing Date: December 15, 2024\n\n1. Executive Summary\nThis memorandum summarizes the environmental issues identified during review of the Phase I Environmental Site Assessment (Phase I ESA) and supporting environmental documents for Buyer’s proposed acquisition of the approximately 14.7-acre former manufacturing/warehouse complex located at 4820 Lakeshore Industrial Drive, Toledo, Ohio (the “Property”) from Breckenridge Manufacturing Co. (“Seller”). Each issue is assigned a severity rating using the four-tier scale defined in Section 3.\nThe Greenfield Environmental Consultants Inc. Phase I ESA (dated October 25, 2024; ASTM E1527-21) identified two on-site Recognized Environmental Conditions (RECs) — (1) former trichloroethylene (TCE) vapor degreasing operations and an abandoned waste-TCE drum, and (2) former hexavalent chromium electroplating operations. The Phase I ESA also identified one Historical Recognized Environmental Condition (HREC), no Controlled Recognized Environmental Conditions (CRECs), and one de minimis condition.\nOur review identifies several matters that the Phase I ESA did not classify as RECs but that, in our judgment, warrant equivalent concern or further investigation, including: an off-site tetrachloroethylene (PCE) groundwater plume migrating toward the Property from an adjacent former dry cleaner (with the Property located within a designated Groundwater Management Zone and shallow groundwater estimated at only 8 to 15 feet below ground surface); an unregistered, unclosed 2,000-gallon waste-solvent underground storage tank (UST) of unknown status; a former outdoor drum-storage area that corresponds to the location of a documented 2003 Ohio EPA Notice of Violation; and an uncharacterized monitoring well of unknown origin near the property boundary.\nWe further identify multiple discrepancies between Seller’s representations and warranties in the Asset Purchase Agreement and the environmental record, most notably Seller’s failure to disclose the 2003 Ohio EPA Notice of Violation on Schedule 4.12(c) and the omission of two historical USTs from Schedule 4.13 (with a related potential breach of the § 4.13(b) “no UST releases/leaking” representation). These discrepancies may support a claim that the representations are breached and, potentially, that the fraud/intentional-misrepresentation exception to the indemnification cap, basket, and survival period applies.\nFinally, because the Phase I ESA identifies RECs, the Lender’s mandatory conditional requirements are triggered (Phase II ESA, Pollution Legal Liability insurance, possible remediation escrow and remediation plan, and vapor intrusion assessment), none of which have yet been satisfied. The Lender — which has placed the Property in its “Elevated Environmental Risk” category and which notes that AAI failure would expose both Borrower and the Bank to CERCLA liability — has expressly stated it will not fund the Loan based solely on a Phase I ESA that identifies RECs. The Lender also reserves the right to decline funding based on unresolved data gaps, several of which remain open.\nA total of fifty (50) distinct issues are enumerated below. A severity summary table appears in Section 12.\n\n2. Scope of Review and Documents Reviewed\n2.1 Documents Reviewed\nThe following documents were reviewed \n...LEN total chars: 58881","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
