{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_844b7121-f7c8-41ee-9fda-3fb2f8818117","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":" the root cause. The environmental task: the source documents describe a property at **2850 Millrace Road, Dayton, Ohio** owned by Valtec, but the agent's memo header says \"4820 Lakeshore Industrial Drive, Toledo, Lucas County, Ohio... Breckenridge Manufacturing Co.\" — entirely fabricated. This is a hallucination, likely from the model's training data leaking in, or the agent confusing itself.\n\nThis is a serious issue: the agent fabricated the entire transaction context (address, county, seller, lender, loan number, parcel numbers) that does not match the source documents. The grader criteria are keyed to the actual facts (Triton Metals, Central Valley Chemical, Dayton Forge & Die, 2.3-acre Parcel A, etc.) which the agent never addressed because it invented a different scenario.\n\nWhy would the agent do this? Possibly the system prompt's \"method\" emphasis plus the completeness review led it to write a plausible-looking memo, but it filled in transaction details from imagination rather than the record. The agent never even mentions \"Dayton Forge\", \"Central Valley\", \"Triton\" — the actual issues in the record. Instead it wrote about \"TCE vapor degreasing\", \"hexavalent chromium electroplating\", \"dry cleaner PCE plume\" — wait, the dry cleaner PCE plume IS one of the criteria (C-031). And \"waste-solvent UST\" matches Tank 3. So the agent got SOME issues but missed many and fabricated the transaction wrapper.\n\nActually wait — re-reading the deliverable summary: \"former trichloroethylene (TCE) vapor degreasing operations and an abandoned waste-TCE drum\" (this matches C-023 western yard TCE / C-017 drum), \"former hexavalent chromium electroplating operations\" (Building 2 electroplating, C-052/C-034), \"off-site PCE groundwater plume from adjacent former dry cleaner\" (C-031). So the agent DID identify real issues from the record. But it fabricated the address/seller/lender/loan wrapper as Toledo/Breckenridge instead of Dayton/Valtec. And it missed many criteria (45 failed).\n\nSo the core failure: the agent hallucinated the transaction metadata and didn't ground the deliverable in the actual record. It scored 0.15. This is the dominant, fixable, GENERAL mode: **hallucinated/fabricated facts not grounded in the source record**, plus **missing individually-graded issues**.\n\nNow, the general fix (method, not memorized): enforce a grounding step. The system prompt already says \"cite the source document for the specific fact (the exact statute, date, figure, party, provision — read it from the record; do not invent it)\" and \"Do not fabricate.\" Yet the agent fabricated the whole address. So prose has plateaued — this is exactly the signal to climb the ladder.\n\nThe best structural fix: add an enforced **grounding/verification pass** in agent_loop.py (or a tools.py action) that, before accepting the deliverable, requires the agent to verify every concrete factual claim (parties, addresses, dates, figures, statute cites) against the source documents. The existing completeness review focuses on coverage of issues but not on whether the facts are actually grounded. Actually the completeness review step 4 says \"drawing the specific facts from the source documents (cite the source)\" — but it's about gaps, not about checking existing claims for fabrication.\n\nBut here's the thing: the agent fabricated the address in the HEADER. The completeness audit re-lists issues and cross-checks coverage, but it doesn't ask \"is the property address you wrote actually what the documents say?\" A stronger structural fix: a **fact-grounding audit** that specifically checks the high-risk fabricated-prone fields (party names, addresses, dates, dollar amounts, statute citations, document titles) against the source, and flags any that don't appear in the source.\n\nLet me think about what's most general and highest-leverage. The fabricated address is one symptom. The deeper issue across all tasks is: deliverables contain concrete facts that the agent invents rather than reads. A verification step that greps the source for each concrete claim would catch this.\n\nActually, the cleanest enforced mechanism: a second injected review pass (like the existing completeness review) but focused on **grounding/verification**: \"Open your deliverable and your source documents. For every concrete factual statement (party names, addresses, dates, dollar figures, statute/regulation citations, document titles, quantities), confirm it appears verbatim in the source documents you read. If any such fact is NOT supported by the source, either replace it with the source's actual fact or remove it. Do not invent transaction details.\" This is method, generalizes to any task, and targets the dominant failure (hallucination) that prose hasn't fixed.\n\nBut I should be careful: the existing completeness review is one-shot. I could either (a) extend the existing review prompt to add a grounding check, or (b) add a second distinct injected pass. The manual says \"When a failure mode you already targeted with a prose rule still shows up across iterations... climb the ladder and encode the fix as an enforced step rather than a stronger suggestion.\" The \"don't fabricate\" prose is already there and failing. So I should encode a grounding verification as an enforced step.\n\nThe existing completeness review pass is the natural place — it's already an enforced injection that runs once before finishing. I'll strengthen it with an explicit GROUNDING/ANTI-FABRICATION step that's distinct and concrete: verify concrete facts against source, especially party names/addresses/dates/figures/citations, and correct any that aren't in the record. This is method-only.\n\nLet me also consider: should I add it as a separate second pass so the agent does coverage THEN grounding? Two passes might be better but costs more. Given budget, I'll fold a strong grounding section into the existing review (it already runs every time). Actually, the manual explicitly warns about two passes and budget. But the environmental task ran 27 turns / 873s and 3.1M tokens — huge. Adding a grounding step to the same review pass is efficient.\n\nHmm, but actually a concern: the existing review focuses on ADDING missing issues. The fabrication issue is about the agent having ALREADY written wrong facts. Adding a \"verify facts are grounded\" instruction to the review should make the agent re-check the header facts. Let me make the grounding check prominent and early in the review.\n\nLet me check budget before deciding on an experiment. Let me check the budget tool.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the highest-leverage change. The fabrication of an entire wrong address is dramatic. But is it the *dominant* mode across many tasks, or idiosyncratic to this one? The summary shows 12 tasks regressed, many by small amounts (likely noise), and one stuck task (environmental, 0.15). The fabricated address is specific to that task. But \"facts not grounded in source / invented details\" is a general risk.\n\nLet me quickly check one or two more failing tasks to see if fabrication or grounding is a recurring theme, vs just under-coverage. Let me look at a regressed task: litigation invoice (0.92->0.82) and the postnuptial (0.96->0.91).\n\nActually, given my reasoning budget, let me be strategic. The manual strongly warns against over-analyzing. The environmental task is the clearest, most extreme failure (0.15, stuck). The fabrication of the property address is a glaring, concrete, generalizable failure: the agent wrote a deliverable whose core subject (the property, the seller, the lender, the loan) does not match the source record at all. Even if other tasks are less extreme, an enforced grounding check is a safe, general improvement that can only help (it forces the agent to verify facts against source) and directly attacks \"do not fabricate\" which prose already says but the agent ignores.\n\nLet me verify this fabrication pattern appears in at least one other task to confirm generality, then make the edit. Let me check the postnuptial task quickly (regressed) and the litigation invoice.\n\nActually, let me be efficient and check budget first, then do a quick check of 2 more tasks' deliverables for grounding issues, then edit.","signature":""}],"model":"accounts/fireworks/models/glm-5p2","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b956bad2-da4b-4332-b834-7a09f6f0b7da","uuid":"f7d3c5a9-7a80-48dc-8640-abfd8b288291"}
