{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-9298113ee84e214c","type":"tool_result","content":"### FILE: environmental-issues-memo.docx\n          ENVIRONMENTAL DUE DILIGENCE ISSUES MEMORANDUM  \n          TO:         David Weir / Marcus Choi, Managing Partners, Cornerstone         Industrial Partners LLC             CC:         Nadia Khoury, Esq., Bridgewell & Hatch         LLP; Sarah Castellano, Esq., Whitfield & Crane LLP             FROM:         Environmental Due Diligence Review             RE:         Phase I ESA and Supporting         Environmental Document Review — Proposed Acquisitions of 4820         Lakeshore Industrial Drive, Toledo, Ohio and 2850 Millrace Road, Dayton,         Ohio             DATE:         [Date of Memo]             PRIVILEGED & CONFIDENTIAL — ATTORNEY                 WORK PRODUCT / PREPARED IN ANTICIPATION OF TRANSACTION  \n       1. Executive Summary  \n      This memorandum reports the findings of our review of the Phase I         Environmental Site Assessments (Phase I ESAs) and supporting         environmental documents assembled in connection with Cornerstone         Industrial Partners LLC’s (    “    Cornerstone    ”         or         “    Buyer    ”    ) proposed         acquisitions of two Ohio industrial properties: (i)             4820 Lakeshore                 Industrial Drive, Toledo, Lucas County, Ohio         (the         “    Toledo Property    ”    ),         to be acquired from Breckenridge Manufacturing Co. (    “    Breckenridge    ”    ) for         $8,750,000 with acquisition financing from Great Lakes Capital Bank         (the         “    Lender    ”    ); and (ii)             2850 Millrace Road, Dayton, Montgomery                 County, Ohio         (the         “    Dayton Property    ”    ), to be acquired from Valtec         Manufacturing Holdings Inc. (    “    Valtec    ”    ) for $4,200,000.  \n      Both Phase I ESAs identified recognized environmental conditions (RECs)         requiring Phase II investigation. Our review, however, identified a         number of             additional issues, classification concerns, data gaps, and                 contractual discrepancies         that are not fully captured in the Phase I         ESA conclusions and that bear directly on the acquisition decision, the         Lender’s conditions to funding, and the availability of CERCLA defenses.         The most significant of these are summarized below and detailed in         Sections 4 through 6.  \n          Most significant issues:  \n              The Toledo Phase I ESA did not classify the off-site                 tetrachloroethylene (PCE) groundwater plume from the adjacent Lake                 Erie Dry Cleaning facility as a recognized environmental                 condition    , even though that plume is documented to be migrating         toward the Toledo Property, has been detected at 87 µg/L (17.4 times         the Ohio standard) only 120 feet from the property boundary, and has         placed the property within a designated Ohio EPA Groundwater         Management Zone. The Lender’s due diligence letter expressly         required evaluation of off-site plumes and identification of any         such migrating condition as a REC.             (Critical)  \n              The Dayton Phase I ESA classified the former underground storage                 tanks (USTs) as a historical recognized environmental condition                 (HREC) based on a 2011 Voluntary Action Program (VAP) No Further                 Action (NFA) letter, but the closure of the 4,000-gallon waste oil                 UST (Tank 3) was never completed or documented         — analytical         results were never received, no closure letter was issued for Tank         3, and no supplemental report was ever located.             (Critical)  \n              The Dayton Phase I ESA’s HREC classification of the former Central                 Valley Chemical Co. operations (Building 3) rests on the same 2011                 VAP NFA letter, which by its own terms covers only a 2.3-acre                 “        Parcel A        ”                 in the southern portion of the site and                 “        does not address                 environmental conditions in areas of the Subject Property outside                 the Parcel A boundary.        ”         Building 3 lies outside Parcel A.             (High)  \n              Breckenridge’s environmental and UST representations in the Toledo                 Asset Purchase Agreement appear to be breached or inaccurate         in         several respects, including the omission of two historical USTs from         Schedule 4.13 and the failure to disclose the 2003 Ohio EPA Notice         of Violation.             (High)  \n      A complete inventory of issues with severity ratings appears in Section         7 (Summary Table).  \n        2. Documents Reviewed  \n      The following documents were reviewed in preparing this memorandum:  \n                           No.  \n          Document  \n          Property  \n          Date  \n            1  \n          Phase I ESA —         Greenfield         Environmental         Consultants         Inc. (Lauren         Haddad, P.E.),         GEC-2024-0347  \n          Toledo  \n          Oct. 25, 2024  \n            2  \n          Phase I ESA —         Terravista         Environmental         Consulting         Inc. (Rachel         Ostrander, P.G.),         TEC-2025-0347  \n          Dayton  \n          Apr. 18, 2025  \n            3  \n          Asset Purchase         Agreement         (excerpt) —         Breckenridge Mfg.         Co. & Cornerstone         Industrial         Partners LLC  \n          Toledo  \n          Sept. 1, 2024  \n            4  \n          Environmental Due         Diligence         Requirements         Letter — Great         Lakes Capital         Bank (Janet Pham)  \n          Toledo  \n          Sept. 10, 2024  \n            5  \n          Ohio EPA Response         Letter — DERR,         Northwest         District Office         (Thomas Kessler)  \n          Toledo  \n          Sept. 28, 2024  \n            6  \n          EDR Database         Summary         (spreadsheet) —         Environmental         Data Resources         Inc.  \n          Toledo  \n          Sept. 15, 2024  \n            7  \n          Environmental         Database Search         Summary —         GeoSearch Data         Systems,         GS-2025-04817  \n          Dayton  \n          Mar. 28, 2025  \n            8  \n          UST Closure         Report —         Redland         Environmental         Services (David         Renner, P.E.),         RES-04-0287  \n          Dayton  \n          Nov. 12, 2004  \n           3. Severity Rating Scale  \n      Each issue is assigned a severity rating using the following scale:  \n                         Rating  \n          Meaning  \n                CRITICAL  \n          Issue that may jeopardize the         transaction, pose substantial         environmental liability or         remediation cost, or reflect a         fundamental deficiency in the due         diligence that must be resolved         before closing. Potential         deal-breaker absent remediation,         insurance, escrow, or         re-negotiation.  \n                HIGH  \n          Significant environmental condition         or contractual/regulatory issue         requiring investigation,         remediation, negotiation, or         specific action at or before         closing. Substantial cost or         liability potential.  \n                MEDIUM  \n          Notable issue requiring follow-up,         clarification, additional         investigation, or monitoring.         Moderate cost or liability         potential, or a documentation gap         that should be closed.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b956bad2-da4b-4332-b834-7a09f6f0b7da","uuid":"abb1382c-b844-4ce3-895e-93fef6504e83","timestamp":"2026-06-27T03:40:09.940Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"### FILE: environmental-issues-memo.docx\n          ENVIRONMENTAL DUE DILIGENCE ISSUES MEMORANDUM  \n          TO:         David Weir / Marcus Choi, Managing Partners, Cornerstone         Industrial Partners LLC             CC:         Nadia Khoury, Esq., Bridgewell & Hatch         LLP; Sarah Castellano, Esq., Whitfield & Crane LLP             FROM:         Environmental Due Diligence Review             RE:         Phase I ESA and Supporting         Environmental Document Review — Proposed Acquisitions of 4820         Lakeshore Industrial Drive, Toledo, Ohio and 2850 Millrace Road, Dayton,         Ohio             DATE:         [Date of Memo]             PRIVILEGED & CONFIDENTIAL — ATTORNEY                 WORK PRODUCT / PREPARED IN ANTICIPATION OF TRANSACTION  \n       1. Executive Summary  \n      This memorandum reports the findings of our review of the Phase I         Environmental Site Assessments (Phase I ESAs) and supporting         environmental documents assembled in connection with Cornerstone         Industrial Partners LLC’s (    “    Cornerstone    ”         or         “    Buyer    ”    ) proposed         acquisitions of two Ohio industrial properties: (i)             4820 Lakeshore                 Industrial Drive, Toledo, Lucas County, Ohio         (the         “    Toledo Property    ”    ),         to be acquired from Breckenridge Manufacturing Co. (    “    Breckenridge    ”    ) for         $8,750,000 with acquisition financing from Great Lakes Capital Bank         (the         “    Lender    ”    ); and (ii)             2850 Millrace Road, Dayton, Montgomery                 County, Ohio         (the         “    Dayton Property    ”    ), to be acquired from Valtec         Manufacturing Holdings Inc. (    “    Valtec    ”    ) for $4,200,000.  \n      Both Phase I ESAs identified recognized environmental conditions (RECs)         requiring Phase II investigation. Our review, however, identified a         number of             additional issues, classification concerns, data gaps, and                 contractual discrepancies         that are not fully captured in the Phase I         ESA conclusions and that bear directly on the acquisition decision, the         Lender’s conditions to funding, and the availability of CERCLA defenses.         The most significant of these are summarized below and detailed in         Sections 4 through 6.  \n          Most significant issues:  \n              The Toledo Phase I ESA did not classify the off-site                 tetrachloroethylene (PCE) groundwater plume from the adjacent Lake                 Erie Dry Cleaning facility as a recognized environmental                 condition    , even though that plume is documented to be migrating         toward the Toledo Property, has been detected at 87 µg/L (17.4 times         the Ohio standard) only 120 feet from the property boundary, and has         placed the property within a designated Ohio EPA Groundwater         Management Zone. The Lender’s due diligence letter expressly         required evaluation of off-site plumes and identification of any         such migrating condition as a REC.             (Critical)  \n              The Dayton Phase I ESA classified the former underground storage                 tanks (USTs) as a historical recognized environmental condition                 (HREC) based on a 2011 Voluntary Action Program (VAP) No Further                 Action (NFA) letter, but the closure of the 4,000-gallon waste oil                 UST (Tank 3) was never completed or documented         — analytical         results were never received, no closure letter was issued for Tank         3, and no supplemental report was ever located.             (Critical)  \n              The Dayton Phase I ESA’s HREC classification of the former Central                 Valley Chemical Co. operations (Building 3) rests on the same 2011                 VAP NFA letter, which by its own terms covers only a 2.3-acre                 “        Parcel A        ”                 in the southern portion of the site and                 “        does not address                 environmental conditions in areas of the Subject Property outside                 the Parcel A boundary.        ”         Building 3 lies outside Parcel A.             (High)  \n              Breckenridge’s environmental and UST representations in the Toledo                 Asset Purchase Agreement appear to be breached or inaccurate         in         several respects, including the omission of two historical USTs from         Schedule 4.13 and the failure to disclose the 2003 Ohio EPA Notice         of Violation.             (High)  \n      A complete inventory of issues with severity ratings appears in Section         7 (Summary Table).  \n        2. Documents Reviewed  \n      The following documents were reviewed in preparing this memorandum:  \n                           No.  \n          Document  \n          Property  \n          Date  \n            1  \n          Phase I ESA —         Greenfield         Environmental         Consultants         Inc. (Lauren         Haddad, P.E.),         GEC-2024-0347  \n          Toledo  \n          Oct. 25, 2024  \n            2  \n          Phase I ESA —         Terravista         Environmental         Consulting         Inc. (Rachel         Ostrander, P.G.),         TEC-2025-0347  \n          Dayton  \n          Apr. 18, 2025  \n            3  \n          Asset Purchase         Agreement         (excerpt) —         Breckenridge Mfg.         Co. & Cornerstone         Industrial         Partners LLC  \n          Toledo  \n          Sept. 1, 2024  \n            4  \n          Environmental Due         Diligence         Requirements         Letter — Great         Lakes Capital         Bank (Janet Pham)  \n          Toledo  \n          Sept. 10, 2024  \n            5  \n          Ohio EPA Response         Letter — DERR,         Northwest         District Office         (Thomas Kessler)  \n          Toledo  \n          Sept. 28, 2024  \n            6  \n          EDR Database         Summary         (spreadsheet) —         Environmental         Data Resources         Inc.  \n          Toledo  \n          Sept. 15, 2024  \n            7  \n          Environmental         Database Search         Summary —         GeoSearch Data         Systems,         GS-2025-04817  \n          Dayton  \n          Mar. 28, 2025  \n            8  \n          UST Closure         Report —         Redland         Environmental         Services (David         Renner, P.E.),         RES-04-0287  \n          Dayton  \n          Nov. 12, 2004  \n           3. Severity Rating Scale  \n      Each issue is assigned a severity rating using the following scale:  \n                         Rating  \n          Meaning  \n                CRITICAL  \n          Issue that may jeopardize the         transaction, pose substantial         environmental liability or         remediation cost, or reflect a         fundamental deficiency in the due         diligence that must be resolved         before closing. Potential         deal-breaker absent remediation,         insurance, escrow, or         re-negotiation.  \n                HIGH  \n          Significant environmental condition         or contractual/regulatory issue         requiring investigation,         remediation, negotiation, or         specific action at or before         closing. Substantial cost or         liability potential.  \n                MEDIUM  \n          Notable issue requiring follow-up,         clarification, additional         investigation, or monitoring.         Moderate cost or liability         potential, or a documentation gap         that should be closed.","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
